 1. Make sure to install JMeter&#39;s self-signed certificate onto the device. The file is called **ApacheJMeterTemporaryRootCA.crt** and it&#39;s being generated in &quot;bin&quot; folder of your JMeter installation when you start the [HTTP(S) Test Script Recorder][1]
 2. You might also need to amend your application [Network Security Configuration][2] in order to allow usage of the self-signed certificates 

    - add the next line to `application` section of your application [manifest][3]

            android:networkSecurityConfig=&quot;@xml/network_security_config&quot;

    - add `network_security_config` file to `base/src/{packageMain}/res` folder and put the following content  there

            &lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; encoding=&quot;utf-8&quot;?&gt;
            &lt;network-security-config&gt;
                &lt;debug-overrides&gt;
                    &lt;trust-anchors&gt;
                        &lt;!-- Trust user added CAs while debuggable only --&gt;
                        &lt;certificates src=&quot;user&quot;/&gt;
                    &lt;/trust-anchors&gt;
                &lt;/debug-overrides&gt;
            &lt;/network-security-config&gt;

 3. Build your application in [debug mode][4]
 4. That&#39;s it, you should be able to record your application traffic now

Check out [Recording Using Android Devices][5] article for more information if needed


