This is where the issue is..

Firstly, learn to use standard notations and not Microsoft specific such as (__int64) which is effectively same as long long int but may need to be exclusively replaced so on standard toolchains. Secondly, you&#39;re typecasting a double to an int and then wondering where the decimal point has gone. Also `%d` is used for integers. Had you not typecasted to integer, still it wouldn&#39;t have taken the decimal value. 


Such questions attract downvotes. I would suggest you to debug your code using a debugger first. Good luck :)


The code is as simple as this btw,




    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    
    main(argc,argv)
    const char** argv;
    {
        int numer1 = 0;
        int denom1 = 0;
        int numer2 = 0;
        int denom2 = 0;
        scanf(&quot;%d %d %d %d &quot;,&amp;numer1,&amp;denom1,&amp;numer2,&amp;denom2);    //don&#39;t forget zero logic
        double frac1 = (double)numer1/(double)denom1;
        double frac2 = (double)numer2/(double)denom2;
        printf (&quot;Whatever you want to print....&quot;);
    return 0;
    }


Also learn to use [good nomenclature][1]


  [1]: https://www.fluentcpp.com/2017/01/30/how-to-choose-good-names/

When dividing two integers, the result is the integer quotient. Any remainder is discarded. So, for example the code

    int a = 7;
    int b = 2;
    int c = a / b;
    double d = a / b;
 
will set `c` to 3. 

It will also set `d` to 3. That&#39;s because the division is performed as integer division, and then the result is converted to a `double`.

To get the correct value for `d`, you need to cast one or both of the integers to a `double`. For example

    double d = (double)a / b;
    double d = a / (double)b;
    double d = (double)a / (double)b;
 
will all set `d` to 3.5

So my suggestion is that you introduce two more variables to hold the fractions as `double` values and then do the multiplication and division:

    //compute the fractions as doubles
    double fraction1 = (double)a / (double)b;
    double fraction2 = (double)c / (double)d;

    //multiply the fractions
    f = fraction1 * fraction2;

    //divide the fractions
    m = fraction1 / fraction2;

Given fractions `a/b` and `c/d`:

The `a / b` in `double e = (a / b)` is _integer_ division.  The quotient&#39;s fractional remainder is lost.

I&#39;d recommend to perform the fraction multiplication using integer math only.

`a/b &#215; c/d` --&gt; `(a*c)/(b*d)`

See also [Euclidean algorithm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm#Implementations)

    long long gcd(long long n, long long m) {
      while (n) {
        long long remainder = m % n;
        m = n;
        n = remainder;
      }
      return m;
    }

      ...
      long long product_num = (long long)a * c;
      long long product_den = (long long)b * d;

      // At this point, code could simplify the product by looking for a common factor.
      long long common = gcd(product_num, product_den);
      if (common) {
        product_num /= common;
        product_den /= common; 
      }

      printf(&quot;The resulting fraction is %lld/%lld\n&quot;, product_num, product_den);
      printf(&quot;The decimal representation is %g\n&quot;, 1.0*product_num/product_den);

Note: `a/b &#247; c/d` is the same as `a/b &#215; d/c`.

